    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-05-08T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-05-08T02:00:00-05:00" n="658"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d658">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">601.4161/5–850: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d658fn1">This telegram was relayed to London, Bucharest,
                        Budapest, Praha, and Warsaw at 7:10 a. m., on May 8.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-05-08T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 8, 1950—10 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1311. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 367 May 1.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d658fn2">Not printed.</note> As indicated <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 890 March 20,<note n="3" xml:id="d658fn3">Not printed. The
                        Embassy stated that it believed that the placing of restrictions on Soviet
                        diplomats in the United States in the current temper of the American people
                        “would serve as continuing reminder to public of unsatisfactory treatment US
                        personnel Moscow.” (601.4161/3–2050)</note> we are dubious whether
                    institution by Department restrictions of travel Soviet diplomats would have
                    ameliorative effect situation Moscow or satellites. While Embassy would welcome
                    institution such restrictions US from standpoint general considerations, we
                    would regret it if such action should result in further restrictions on our
                    travel here. Department aware that travel we now able perform is useful, and
                    that recently we have found it possible make rather extensive trips (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>s 1005 April 1 and 1154 April 17<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d658fn4">Latter telegram not printed, but see footnote 4, <ref
                            target="#pg_1135">p. 1135</ref>.</note>).</p>
                <p>If US restrictions decided on, we urge they be strictly reciprocal. That
                    connection note that general demand that permission be obtained as distinct from
                    simple notification in case travel outside specified radius (Depcirair August
                    19, 1949, 8:10 a. m.<note n="5" xml:id="d658fn5">
                        <ref target="frus1949v05#pg_648">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1949, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 648</ref>.</note>) might cause us
                    trouble. While notification plus control tickets is comparable to permission, in
                    majority cases which involve automobile transportation to nearby spots outside
                    Moscow notification is minor annoyance whereas obtainment permission likely be
                    onerous.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
